neath that energy, we are not as clear as we ought to be about desired outcomes, the kinds of learning needed to achieve these, and how those kinds of learning actually occur. This volume is the first of its kind to bring together scholars from inside Jewish education and from the learning sciences. It offers a set of critical perspectives on learning, sometimes borrowing models from other domains (such as science) and sometimes examining specific domains within Jewish education (such as havruta learning or the learning of Jewish history). Collectively, these contributions help to advance a smarter, sharper conversation about Jewish learning that matters.  afunded by Jack, Joseph and Morton Mandel Center for Studies in Jewish Education  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aJewish religious education. 0aJewsxEducation. 0aJews-Education. 0aJudaismxStudy and teaching. 0aJudaism-Study and teaching. 7aRELIGION / Education.2bisacsh  aEducational Outcomes.  aEducational Philosophy.  aJewish education.  aJudaism.  aLearning Science.  aReligious Education.  aTeaching and Learning.1 aDorph, Rena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGottlieb, Eli, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKelman, Ari Y., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKolodner, Janet L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKress, Jeffrey S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKress, Jeffrey, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLevisohn, Jon A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.g